1
00:00:04,976 --> 00:00:10,046
We are operating on the basis 
of acquired prejudice.

2
00:00:10,266 --> 00:00:13,746
[Acquired Prejudice | Mental Impressions]

3
00:00:13,752 --> 00:00:18,502
So … And Bhakti Vinod Ṭhākur
says in one place,

4
00:00:18,602 --> 00:00:21,495
he makes
an interesting observation.

5
00:00:21,495 --> 00:00:27,505
He says that when we acquired
the prejudice, it was without thinking,

6
00:00:27,505 --> 00:00:32,525
but when it comes time to give up
that acquired prejudice,

7
00:00:32,525 --> 00:00:35,505
then we have to think about it
for a long time.

8
00:00:35,505 --> 00:00:38,505
We are not … So many things
we have to consider.

9
00:00:38,505 --> 00:00:45,305
They use a word in India 
in Sanskrit. It’s called saṁskār.

10
00:00:47,466 --> 00:00:51,466
And saṁskār is translated
in different ways,

11
00:00:51,475 --> 00:00:54,765
but it means like, 
‘mental impressions’.

12
00:00:54,765 --> 00:00:58,765
Like a printing machine
makes an impression.

13
00:00:58,765 --> 00:01:01,275
So what they mean 
by saṁskār is:

14
00:01:01,275 --> 00:01:06,305
we’ve lived many times, in many life forms—
reincarnation and all that,

15
00:01:06,305 --> 00:01:10,305
and each time you’re getting
one impression, another impression,

16
00:01:10,305 --> 00:01:12,625
another impression, 
another impression,

17
00:01:12,835 --> 00:01:18,275
and this is, you can say,
clouding our consciousness.

18
00:01:18,502 --> 00:01:26,262
So when we try to reflect, “Who am I? 
What is my position in the world?

19
00:01:26,262 --> 00:01:31,022
Where have I come from? 
Where am I going?”—all these things;

20
00:01:31,753 --> 00:01:41,253
it’s being filtered through the clouds
of acquired prejudice or impressions.

21
00:01:41,253 --> 00:01:44,523
In the first verse of Śikṣāṣṭakam,

22
00:01:44,523 --> 00:01:47,283
which is Mahāprabhu’s 
famous eight prayers,

23
00:01:47,283 --> 00:01:50,283
in the first one He says,

24
00:01:50,283 --> 00:01:56,503
ceto-darpaṇa-mārjanaṁ
bhava-mahādāvāgni-nirvāpaṇaṁ

25
00:01:56,663 --> 00:02:02,513
śreyaḥ-kairava-chandrikā-vitaraṇaṁ 
vidyā-vadhū-jīvanam

26
00:02:02,513 --> 00:02:06,503
ānandāmbudhi-vardhanaṁ 
prati-padaṁ pūrṇāmṛtāsvādanaṁ

27
00:02:06,503 --> 00:02:10,513
sarvātma-snapanaṁ paraṁ
vijayate śrī-kṛṣṇa-saṅkīrtanam

28
00:02:10,803 --> 00:02:16,993
So in the first line He says, 
“The mind is like a mirror.”

29
00:02:17,522 --> 00:02:23,862
Like we’ve got this mirror 
right here as a prop.

30
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:29,500
So, they are saying, a mirror, 
like this mirror, if we don’t clean it,

31
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:33,530
it will get a layer, another layer of 
dust, another layer of dust,

32
00:02:33,530 --> 00:02:38,520
and when it gets sufficiently covered
by different layers of dust,

33
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:42,520
you won’t be able to see yourself
reflected in the mirror.

34
00:02:42,930 --> 00:02:49,540
So in Bhagavad-gītā [3.38]
Kṛṣṇa says in this one sloka,

35
00:02:52,658 --> 00:02:57,448
yatholbenāvṛto garbhas, 
He compares …

36
00:02:57,790 --> 00:03:02,290
You know, we have the modes 
of ignorance, passion and goodness

37
00:03:02,518 --> 00:03:07,998
as different layers 
or coverings of consciousness.

38
00:03:08,264 --> 00:03:12,264
One’s like dust, one’s thicker,
different things.

39
00:03:15,338 --> 00:03:21,768
So the method to overcome
acquired prejudice

40
00:03:21,813 --> 00:03:31,513
is to take shelter at the lotus feet 
of Sādhu, Śāstra, Guru and Vaiṣṇava.

41
00:03:32,093 --> 00:03:37,503
So in the most primal 
guru-mantra it says,

42
00:03:37,525 --> 00:03:41,505
oṁ ajñāna-timirāndhasya
jñānāñjana-śalākayā

43
00:03:41,505 --> 00:03:44,785
cakṣur unmīlitaṁ yena 
tasmai śrī-gurave namaḥ

44
00:03:45,174 --> 00:03:52,614
The disciple is offering respectful
obeisanses to the guru, saying,

45
00:03:52,774 --> 00:03:57,514
“My eyes were like cataracted.”

46
00:03:57,514 --> 00:04:00,254
You know cataracts?
Do you know what cataract is?

47
00:04:00,254 --> 00:04:04,724
Old people get it very often.
Like, they can’t see properly anymore.

48
00:04:04,724 --> 00:04:09,534
So in this sloka
the disciple is saying,

49
00:04:09,534 --> 00:04:16,534
“My eyes they have like cataracts.”
Of what? Acquired prejudice and bias.

50
00:04:16,534 --> 00:04:21,634
So through … “I’m seeing everything 
through this bias or acquired prejudice.”

51
00:04:21,634 --> 00:04:23,504
Then he is saying in the prayer,

52
00:04:23,504 --> 00:04:27,784
“But you—I am praying to my guru—
you’re like a surgeon.”

53
00:04:27,784 --> 00:04:30,514
You know laser surgery?

54
00:04:30,514 --> 00:04:33,514
That’s how they do cataract surgery 
in the modern world.

55
00:04:33,514 --> 00:04:36,344
So he’s saying like, 
“With pinpoint light—

56
00:04:36,344 --> 00:04:43,504
with the light of scriptures
and the teachings of the guru-varga

57
00:04:43,504 --> 00:04:48,259
you remove the cataracts
of bias and prejudice of my eyes,

58
00:04:48,269 --> 00:04:50,509
and now I can see things properly.”

59
00:04:50,509 --> 00:04:57,899
And, back in the Śikṣāṣṭakam sloka,

60
00:04:58,179 --> 00:05:01,549
where they’re comparing 
the mind to a mirror

61
00:05:01,549 --> 00:05:04,519
that has accumulated
so many layers of dust,

62
00:05:04,519 --> 00:05:08,859
He says, “Ceto-darpaṇa”—
darpaṇa means ‘mirror’, mārjanaṁ,

63
00:05:08,859 --> 00:05:10,519
and ceto means ‘consciousness’.

64
00:05:10,519 --> 00:05:15,509
So He’s saying, “The mirror of your mind,
your consciousness, your way of seeing

65
00:05:15,509 --> 00:05:20,249
will be cleansed
by chanting Kṛṣṇa-nām

66
00:05:20,249 --> 00:05:25,361
under the direction
of your guru and Vaiṣṇava.”

